@LyricalTokarev33 So how did Wendy decode the command phrases for these supposedly hardwired Xenomorph Drone responses? Being a super smart AI mind doesn't give you magic powers - you would still need data to work from, some sort of starting point from which to work out which clicks and whistles will have the desired effect, and even then there is lore within the Alien franchise suggesting that Xenomorph hive interactions  are at least partially mediated by pheromonal signals that Wendy would have no means of mimicking no matter how big her robot brain is supposed to be without a great deal of lab equipment that Alien; Earth never shows her using,

But lets put all that to one side; lets ignore all the logical issues and continuity errors and simply assume that you are right, and this is what Alien; Earth is trying to say - it is still terrible writing and story telling technique because it requires so much guess work on the part of the audience without any of it being supported by anything we actually see or hear on screen. The old story teller's advice is 'show, don't tell', but Alien; Earth neither shows nor tells that which, according to your interpretation, is important information about how Wendy is doing all this and how Xenomorph physiology and social interaction work that the audience needs to make sense of the plot line. 'She can do it because Ai is magic and Xenomorphs are really just misunderstood obedient puppies with an unfortunate tendency to get over excited and bite' is an insufficient explanation. The internal logic of a fictional universe has to fit together and make sense for a story to be compelling, and in  Alien; Earth it just doesn't.

As an example, why is Wendy the only hybrid who can do all this? Seven episodes in out of eight in the season, Alien; Earth  has never shown us what it is that so completely separates Wendy from  the others of her kind and allows her to control technology, and apparently Xenomorphs, at will. She is literally the embodiment of the 'magic girl who is the key to everything' trope which is a justly reviled lazy plot device employed all too often these days by writers that either lack the talent to come up with anything more interesting or simply can't be bothered to try.

@tarekomar54 - Your claim is invalid, because it is devoid of common sense.  You think that an android which doesn't have enough brains to figure out how she's being manipulated by prodigy boy, is smart enough to not only listen to the xenomorph's "language", but to determine what every sound means and has a full understanding of the syntax?  Are you being serious here, or are you just one of the show's writers?  

Being able to make noises at certain frequencies, does not equal being able to "mimic a queen's commands/signals".  The bucket of bolts has never heard a queen's signals.  It's only heard the babbling of a drone, with no context to put the sounds to.  You can't just hear a few notes and clicks from an animal and suddenly realize, "Oh!  That means he has a thorn in his paw!"

Look up what happens when a non-native speaker goes to a foreign land and starts repeating noises they hear from other people around them.  The end result is worse than Monty Python's Hungarian to English phrase book...

